title.narrative: OUTPUT 3.5: EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS AND RESPONSE - HIV-AIDS AND CHILD PROTECTION

description.narrative: Output 3.5 Government and non-governmental partners adopt risk-informed approaches to emergency preparedness, planning and response to humanitarian needs for child protection and HIV, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids (Covid), Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid), Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 3 - Children and adolescents are increasingly protected from exposure to HIV and AIDS, violence, abuse, exploitation and harmful cultural practices, and benefit from increased access to prevention, care, treatment, support, justice and other services needed to ensure their physical, mental and social wellbeing.

title.narrative: Output 3.5 Government and non-governmental partners adopt risk-informed approaches to emergency preparedness, planning and responseto humanitarian needs for child protection and HIV

description.narrative: UNICEF collaboration with government and civil society partners in the response to protection needs of children in humanitarian situations benefitted 58,897 children (33,525 girls, 25,372 boys) and 735 adults (393 men, 342 women). UNICEF scaled up capacity building of the social service workforce in drought affected counties and refugee camps, whereby 320 (222 male, 98 female) children protection volunteers and 65 Children Officers (33 men, 32 female) were trained,;improving the quality of services to at risk children. Engagement with parents and caregivers further enhanced home-based care and support for 5,901 (3,430 boys, 2,471 girls) children separated from their families. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:05/01/2022
